sect2.p:
We cross-matched the GZ CEERS sample with the F23 sample, resulting in 3069 galaxies within a 5 arcsec separation which were morphologically classified by both studies. Note that F23 also visually classify all of their galaxies as either smooth or featured, but do not investigate this further in their original study. Here, we compare their featured vote fraction with the GZ featured vote fraction in Fig. 2. The red circles in Fig. 2 show the mean featured vote fraction from F23 in equal sized bins of GZ CEERS featured vote fraction; the mean roughly traces the 1:1 line between the two vote fractions, although F23 tend to be more likely to classify a galaxy as featured, whereas GZ volunteers are more ‘pessimistic’. Similarly, the blue circles show the mean GZ CEERS featured vote fraction in equal sized bins of featured vote fraction from F23, which do not trace the 1:1 line, once again demonstrating that GZ volunteers are less likely to classify a galaxy as featured than F23. While there are not any galaxies which the GZ volunteers classify as featured but F23 do not (bottom right corner of Fig. 2), there are 62 galaxies which GZ volunteers do not classify as featured (
; top left corner of Fig. 2), but F23 do (
). Examples of such galaxies are shown in Fig. 3.

